<h2 id="principles">Principles</h2>

<p>Here are a few of the principles that are top of mind for me to apply going in. Some are innate in my behaviors, others require conscious effort on my part. I wrote them down so I could refer back to them if I need a waypoint.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Say ‚Äúgood morning‚Äù</strong>: I‚Äôm leading remotely during the middle of a pandemic. Physical and communication cures are lacking. Show them I‚Äôm human and present.</li>
  <li><strong>Listen, don‚Äôt assume</strong>: There will be a lot that I don‚Äôt know or understand, a lot of context I lack. Be patient.</li>
  <li><strong>Focus on high-leverage activities</strong>: It will be easy to fall for the feeling of being busy and diving into work that feels good. In particular, shy away from deep technical work. It‚Äôs much more important to hire more software engineers than sling code.</li>
  <li><strong>Work on the business</strong>: See above.</li>
  <li><strong>Manage towards the result you want; hope is not a strategy.</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Have a bias towards action; have a sense of urgency.</strong></li>
  <li><strong>For long feedback loops, focus on the inputs and not the results</strong>: There will come a time when I‚Äôm not sure if I‚Äôm doing the right things. I remember recruiting my first engineer for Duo Austin was taking longer than I‚Äôd like. I wasn‚Äôt sure if I was doing the right things. Zack Urlocker, our COO, framed recruiting as an inputs-based system. If it takes 100 LinkedIn messages to get a response and 10 responses to get to a candidate that we want to bring onsite and 3 onsite to a hire and if we want to hire 3 people, we know the numbers we need to hit. Eventually we can adjust from the results, but some activities are inherently long cycle.</li>
  <li><strong>Take a beat; slow down your criticism</strong>: A former manager once told me in our final 1:1 before he departed that the #1 thing I could do to improve is to slow down my criticism. It‚Äôs natural for engineers to be critical. But hear what‚Äôs being said first. Sleep on your disagreement. 90% of the time it will dissipate. And the other 10% of the time, you‚Äôll figure out how to frame your solution to bring others along.</li>
  <li><strong>There is no <em>one</em> perfect / right answer; perfect is the enemy of good enough.</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Even if you know the ‚Äúright‚Äù answer, ask others</strong>: It goes much better to front load the work of bringing others along in your ideas.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="priorities">Priorities</h2>

<p>With that said, here‚Äôs my priority thesis for my first 12 months at Strata. They‚Äôre in rough order but not strictly linear.</p>

<ul>
